{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17626071","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17626071"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:33:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:33:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17054"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17054","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17054"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.33,0.5,0.13,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9744"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77013"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9744","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9744"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17054"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62519"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5253"},{"type":"tags","id":"7674"},{"type":"tags","id":"8511"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22922"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23101"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77013","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77013"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman with relapsing-remitting multiple sclerosis is commenced on natalizumab after failing first-line therapy. This medication reduces disease activity by preventing immune cells from entering the central nervous system.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of natalizumab?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inhibits lymphocyte activation in peripheral lymphoid tissue","Suppresses T lymphocyte proliferation in lymph nodes","Blocks alpha-4 integrin on lymphocyte surface membranes","Neutralises inflammatory cytokines in circulation","Enhances regulatory T lymphocyte differentiation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking alpha-4 integrin on lymphocyte surface membranes\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary mechanism of action of natalizumab. This prevents autoreactive T cells from entering the central nervous system where they would cause inflammation and demyelination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibiting lymphocyte activation in peripheral lymphoid tissue\u003C/strong\u003E is not a mechanism of natalizumab, which acts specifically on cell adhesion\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuppressing T lymphocyte proliferation in lymph nodes\u003C/strong\u003E is more characteristic of sphingosine-1-phosphate receptor modulators like fingolimod\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeutralising inflammatory cytokines in circulation\u003C/strong\u003E is not a mechanism used in multiple sclerosis treatment as it can worsen disease\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhancing regulatory T lymphocyte differentiation\u003C/strong\u003E is not a direct mechanism of natalizumab\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy preventing immune cell entry into the central nervous system, natalizumab reduces inflammation and disease activity in multiple sclerosis patients. However, this mechanism also carries a risk of progressive multifocal leukoencephalopathy due to reduced immune surveillance.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Natalizumab prevents T lymphocytes from crossing the blood-brain barrier by blocking alpha-4 integrin.","Multiple sclerosis treatments target different aspects of immune system function to reduce inflammation and disease progression.","Understanding the mechanism of action of multiple sclerosis treatments helps explain their therapeutic effects and potential risks."],"references":["Hauser SL, Cree BAC. Treatment of Multiple Sclerosis: A Review. Am J Med. 2020;133(12):1380-1390.e2. doi:10.1016/j.amjmed.2020.05.049","Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62519"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17054"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62519","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62519"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T22:21:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T22:23:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9744"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77013"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups